Step 2: State scientific question

I want to analysis relationship between PT_Elev and DB. I want to investigate whether people who use different photo apps go to different heights. I can also assume that people who are willing to go to high elevation places will be younger. Besides, the amount of photos also reflect difference between apps.

Step 3: view chart of two variables

# plot a box plot for Flickr and pano with elevation 
boulder %>%
  filter(DB ==  'Pano' | DB == 'Flickr') %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=DB, y=PT_Elev)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

Based on the boxplot, two graphs are really similar to each other. The mean of Pano is little bit higher than Flickr, but the range are smaller than Flicker. We can not get enough imformation for our analysis. Therefore, we need further edit our data and mapping it.

Step 4: Data editation

# to see what is inside DB column.
table(boulder$DB)
## 
##     Flickr OSMP_lands       Pano 
##       6428      48644        447
# pick the Flickr 
boulder_f=boulder[boulder$DB == 'Flickr',]
dim(boulder_f)# check if it is correspond with original data
## [1] 6428   13
# pick the Pano
boulder_p=boulder[boulder$DB == 'Pano',]
dim(boulder_p)# check if it is correspond with original data
## [1] 447  13

Based on the table, we can find out that there is more user of Flickr than Panramio. But how is distribution of photo took by different Apps?

Step 5: Map visualization

# adjust projection to Colorado
boulder_f = st_transform(boulder_f, 26753) 
boulder_p = st_transform(boulder_p, 26753) 
# plot the elevation of all rows
ggplot() +
    geom_sf(data =boulder, aes(color=PT_Elev),
    fill = NA, alpha = .2) + annotation_north_arrow(location='tr', style =north_arrow_fancy_orienteering)+ xlab('Longitude')+ylab('Latitude')+ggtitle('Elevation when taking photos in Boulder')+
    theme_bw()

# plot location of Flicker with its elevation when took photos
ggplot() +
    geom_sf(data =boulder_f, aes(color=PT_Elev),
    fill = NA, alpha = .2) + annotation_north_arrow(location='tr', style =north_arrow_fancy_orienteering)+ xlab('Longitude')+ylab('Latitude')+ggtitle('Flicker:Elevation when taking photos in Boulder')+
    theme_bw()

# plot location of Panramio with its elevation when took photos
ggplot() +
    geom_sf(data =boulder_p, aes(color=PT_Elev),
    fill = NA, alpha = .2) + annotation_north_arrow(location='tr', style =north_arrow_fancy_orienteering)+ xlab('Longitude')+ylab('Latitude')+ggtitle('Panramio:Elevation when taking photos in Boulder')+
    theme_bw()

Based on the map above, we find out that the west part has higher elevation. The distribution pattern is similar for both Panramio and Flickr. Slightly more users use flickr than Panramio in high altitude areas.
